# Blue Nile Anniversary Rings Review {{year}}: Riviera Pavé, Floating Diamond & Every Style Ranked

[Blue Nile's anniversary rings page](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/rings/anniversary-rings?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blue_nile_reviews) spans from a $770 lab-grown Floating Diamond ring in 14K gold to a $19,490 Seven Stone Bezel oval ring with 3.5 CTW of natural diamonds. The most reviewed anniversary ring on the page — by a dominant margin — is the **Riviera Pavé Diamond Ring with 865 verified reviews** across 14K white gold, yellow gold, rose gold, and platinum. Nothing else on this page is close.

Before the rankings, one thing every buyer should understand: **nearly every ring on this page offers both a natural diamond and a lab-grown diamond version.** The natural and lab-grown variants look identical but carry meaningfully different prices — and different long-term value profiles. Most buyers shopping anniversary rings don't realize they're choosing between two completely different markets when they select a diamond type. This guide covers both.

---

## The Natural vs Lab-Grown Decision for Anniversary Rings

This is the most important choice on this page, and Blue Nile's toggle makes it easy to miss.

**Natural diamonds** retain resale value over time — not perfectly, but meaningfully. A natural diamond anniversary ring purchased today will hold a percentage of its value if resold. The 865-review Riviera Pavé buyer pool is built entirely on natural diamond versions.

**Lab-grown diamonds** are chemically identical to natural diamonds and visually indistinguishable. But their market price has dropped significantly over the past few years and continues to drop. A lab-grown diamond purchased today has minimal resale value. This doesn't make lab-grown wrong — it makes it a different purchase. If you're buying an anniversary ring to wear and keep, lab-grown saves real money. If you're buying something you might upgrade or resell, natural is the honest choice.

**On this page:** The Riviera Pavé natural ring at 1/6 ct costs $980. The lab-grown Riviera Pavé at 1/2 ct F-G/VS2-SI1 costs $770 — more diamond for less money. The tradeoff is entirely about what you value: carat weight at low cost (lab) vs. verified buyer confidence and long-term value (natural, 865 reviews).

